The class CR_ClassificationRegister specifies information about the register itself. It is a subclass of the class RegistrationComponents::Register which is defined in ISO 19135. It inherits 1 attribute from ISO 19135 and defines 7 attributes. These 7 attributes had previously been defined in earlier versions of ISO 19135. The same attribute names are used as before to maintain backward compatibility.

This attribute is represented as a CharacterString containing a compact and human-readable designator that is used to uniquely denote that register within the set of registers maintained by the register owner.

This attribute is represented as a CharacterString containing a general statement of the purpose for which items in the register are made available to potential users. It should also specify any limits to the scope of the register and identify the types of applications for which the items are intended. NOTE The scope of a register could be limited by theme, by region, by language or other criteria.
This conditional attribute takes as its value a set of URI's, each referencing information about online resources associated with the register.

This attribute is represented as an instance of class PT_Locale that is used to specify language, country information and character encoding for the proper interpretation of the content of character strings in the register. The values of all character strings in the register are in accordance with the value of of this attribute unless otherwise stated.

This attribute provides a summary of alternative locales used by items in a register to support cultural and linguistic adaptability. Individual items in a register may provide elements of information in additional languages other than the operating language of the register. The attribute represents as a set of instances of PT_Locale, each specifying an additional unique locale used by items in the register. Every member of the set is used by at least one item in the register. The locale of every "alternativeExpression" used by any item in the register shall be included in this set of "PT_Locale" items.
This conditional attribute is represented as an instance of class CR_Version that specifies a unique state in the life of the register.

This conditional attribute is represented as an instance of the class <Date> [ISO 19103] and specifies the (full precision) date of the most recent change to the status of an item in the register was made.
This subtype relationship establishes inheritance from the ISO 19135 RegisterComponents:Register to the CR_ClassificationRegister.
The aggregation association Content connects the class CR_ClassificationRegister to the set of CR_RegisterItem held in the register.
The role “containedItem” connects an instance of the class Register to one or more instances of RegisterItem.
The role register connects an instance of a register item class to a register.

The association "ContentDescription" connects the class CR_ClassificationRegister to one ore more instances of "CR_ItemClass", each of which describes the characteristics of a class of items held in the register.
The role "containedItemClass" describes that the "ItemClass" for the association "ContentDescription" contains the item classes in the register.
The role "register" connects an instance of an item class to a register.

This class describes the form of the registered item used to register a new attribute value for use in the LCML or LUML meta languages as part of a code list. This class inherits the attributesfrom CR_ItemClass and adds the attributes This class adds the attributes: attributeValueName, attributeValueDefinition and associatedCodelist. Note, this approach of defining the attribute values used in a code list as a separate registered element is derived from the IHO Geospatial Information Registry .
The attribute attributeValueName describes the name of the new LCML or LUML model attribute value to be registered.

The attribute attributeValueDefinition describes the definition of the new Land Cover Land Use attribute value to be added to LCML or LUML model to be registered. A reference to the source of the definition may be made through the RE_Reference mechanism defined in ISO 19135.

The attribute associatedCodelist identifies the codelist to which the attribute value applies. The codelist may be a new registered attribute item or it may be an existing code list defined in the LCML or LUML standards. There are many code lists in these standards that have been left for future registration of values. An attribute value item may be associated with more than one code list.

This class describes the form of the registered item used to register a new attribute for use in the LCML or LUML meta languages. This class inherits the attributesfrom CR_ItemClass and adds the attributes: attributeName, attributeDefinition and attributeType which references the code list CR_AttType.
The attribute attributeName describes the name of the new LCML or LUML model attribute to be registered.

The attribute attributeDefinition describes the definition of the new Land Cover Land Use attribute to be added to LCML or LUML model to be registered. A reference to the source of the definition may be made through the RE_Reference mechanism defined in ISO 19135.
The attribute attributeType describes the type of the new LCML or LUML attribute to be registered using the code list CR_AttType.
The code list CR_RoleMultiplicity describes how many instances of one object can be connected to an instance of another class through a given relationship.
0 .. * - Zero or many instances may be associated through a relation.
0 .. * - (Optional) Zero or one instance may be associated through a relation.
1 - One instance may be associated through a relation.
1 .. * - One or many instances may be associated through a relation.
The class CR_Version defines a dataType that uniquely defines a version.

The attribute "versionNumber" is represented as a constrained CharacterString that denotes the version. The CharacterString shall be of the form <first positive integer> <dot> <second positive integer> <letter characters> (“#.#a”), where:
  • <first positive integer> (one or more digits) shall specify the major version designation;
  • <dot> (“.”) shall delimit the <first positive integer> from the <second positive integer> when there is a <second positive integer>;
  • <second positive integer> (one or more digits) shall optionally specify the minor sub-version designation; and
<letters> (one or more characters) shall optionally specify the minor subversion designation. EXAMPLE “2.1a”.
The attribute "versionDate" is represented as an instance of the class <Date> [ISO 19103] that specifies the date (which may be of reduced precision) of the version. EXAMPLE 2002-10-21.

This class inherits four attributes: identifier, name, alternativeName and registerStandard and adds the optional attributes itemDescription. For the LCLU descriptive element register described in this document the attribute itemDescription contains the text string "RulesDescriptor" to identify the registered item describes a rule or operation.

The attribute itemDescription contains the text string "RulesDescriptor" to identify the registered item describes a rule. An example of a rule is an operation where a navigation canal is closed for the winter months and therefore the water level is lowered and the adjacent land is exposed. This is more than just a seasonal change because there are follow-on effects from the winter closure.
The attribute "content" contains an optional character string that permits a fuller description of the item.

This class inherits four attributes: identifier, name, alternativeName and registerStandard and adds the optional attributes itemDescription. For the LCLU legend specification register described in this document the attribute itemDescription contains the text string "LegendSchemaRegister" to identify the registered item describes the classes used within a particular classification system schema or legend. Since this classification schema or legend is specified in an external machine-readable document it will be referenced directly from the legend schema register at the registered item level. Also, the documentation for the classification schema or legend can be referenced using the CI_CItation mechanism from ISO 19115-1.
The attribute itemDescription contains the text string "LegendSchemaRegister" to identify the registered item describes the classes used within a particular classification system schema or legend.

The attribute content contains an optional localized character string that permits a fuller description of the classification system or legend specification. Since this classification schema or legend is specified in an external machine-readable document, it will be referenced directly from the legend schema register at the registered item level. Also the documentation for the classification schema or legend can be referenced using the CI_Citation mechanism from ISO 19115-1.
The documentation can be referenced using the CI_CItation mechanism from ISO 19115-1.

The code list CR_RelationType describes the types of roles that may be associated with the source or target roles in a CR_CharacteristicElementRelation as part of a CR_CharacteristicElementItem to be registered to extend the LCML or LUML meta language.
association - a UML relationship between objects.
subtype - (generalization / specialization) also called a parent/child relationship, in which one object is a type of another inheriting properties from the parent.
aggregation - a relationship where the object can exist independently of the related object. Example: School and student. Delete the school and the students still exist.
composition - a relationship where an object cannot exist independent of the related object. Example: Building and room. Rooms don't exist separate to a building.
realization - a relationship between two objects, where the one model element implements the responsibility specified by the supplier (another model element).

This class inherits from RegiterComponents::RegisterItemClass and realizes RegisterComponents:ContentSchema as defined in ISO 19135 and it contains a description of a class of geographic information items specified in an associated technical standard. The attribute "registerStandard" contains a reference to an external document that describes the structure of the register as implemented and the detailed meaning of the registered item class. The attribute "name" is represented as a CharacterString containing a compact and human-readable designator that is used to denote a class of item.. The attribute "alternativeName" contains a set of zero or more alternative names.
The attribute "name" is represented as a CharacterString containing a compact and human-readable designator that is used to denote a class of item.

The attribute "alternativeName" contains a set of instances of CharacterString, each of which is a translation of the "name" of the CR_ItemClass into a language other than the "operatingLanguage" of the register.
The attribute "registerStandard" contains a reference to an external document that describes the structure of the register as implemented and the detailed meaning of the registered item class.
This subtype relationship establishes inheritance from the ISO 19135 RegisterComponents:RegisterItemClass to the CR_ItemClass.
The association "Categorization" connects each CR_RegisterItem to the instance of "CR_ItemClass" of which describes its content.

This class describes the registered item used to register a Land Cover Land Use dataset. This class inherits the attributes from CR_RegisterItem. The attributes name, definition, legendUsed and documentationReference are added to reference the specific classification scheme or legend used in a particular data set.

The attribute name overwrites the attribute name inherited from RE_RegisterItem and describes the name of the data set. the value of name is unique in the register and can be used together with the attribute status and the date (calculated from the attributes dateTimeAddition, dateTimeSupersession, dateTimeRetirement and dateTimeInvalidation) to form a secondary key to access the register. That is, if one knows the date of the data set and the name of the data set one can determine the classification schema or legend specification that was valid at that time. This means that older data sets that make use of older versions of classification schemas or legends remain valid since the register preserves the status at any time in the past.

The attribute definition overwrites the attribute definition inherited from RE_RegisterItem and provides a description of the of the data set. This attribute is made optional. A full citation of the source of the data set can be made through the RE_Reference mechanism defined in ISO 19135.

The attribute legendUsed identifies the classification schema or legend used. If the classification schema or legend is contained in the legend schema register this can be a reference to that registered item. Alternatively, it can be a reference to an external document. The reference is by the name of the classification schema or legend.
The documentation for the dataset item can be referenced using the CI_CItation mechanism from ISO 19115-1.

This class describes an attribute that can be associated with the new LCML or LUML model element to be registered. An attribute to be registered includes a name specified in the attribute attributeName, a definition specified in the attribute attributeDefinition and a type specified in the attribute attributeType, which refers to a code list CR_AttType.
The attribute attributeName describes the name of the new LCML or LUML model element attribute to be registered.

The attribute attributeDefinition describes the definition of the new LCML or LUML model element attribute to be registered. A reference to the source of the definition may be made through the RE_Reference mechanism defined in ISO 19135.
The attribute attributeType describes the type of the new LCML or LUML model element attribute to be registered using the code list CR_AttType.

This class describes the form of the registered item used to register a rule for use in the LCML or LUML meta languages. This class inherits the attributesfrom CR_ItemClass and adds the attributes: ruleName and ruleDefinition.
The attribute ruleName describes the name of the rule to be registered.
The attribute ruleDefinition describes the definition of the rule to be registered.

This class describes the form of the registered item used to register a new characteristic or element for use in the LCML or LUML meta languages. Since the element being registered is a new metaclass for LCML or LUML it includes attributes that describe the element as a UML model element. This class inherits the attributes from CR_RegisterItem and adds the attributes: metaElementName, metaElementDefinition, metaElementAttributeusing the data type class CR_MetaLangAttribute and associatedRelations using the data type class CR_MetaLangRelation.
The attribute metaElementName describes the name of the new element or characteristic meta language class to be registered.
The attribute metaElementDefinition contains a definition of the new element or characteristic meta language class.

The attribute metaElementAttributes contains a set of associated attributes. Each attribute is associated by name and must either already exist in ISO 19144-2 or ISO 19144-3 or other TC-211 standard such as, ISO 19103 or ISO 19115-1 or be registered using the CR_AttributeItem part of the register. There can be 0 or more attributes. Each attribute is described in CR_MetaLangAttributes.

The attribute associatedRelations describes the relations that may be associated with the new LCML or LUML model element to be registered. There is at least one relation. Each relation is described in the referenced class CR_MetaLangRelation.

This class describes a relation that can be associated with the new LCML or LUML model element to be registered. An relation to be registered includes a name specified in the attribute relationName, a definition specified in the attribute relationDefinition a type specified in the attribute relationType, which refers to a code list CR_RelationType and the two roles, the source role and the target role of the relation represented in the attributes sourceRole and targetRole which refer to the code list CRRoleDescription.
The attribute relationName describes the name of the relation to be associated with the new LCML or LUML model element to be registered.
The attribute relationDefinition describes the definition of the relation to be associated with the new LCML or LUML model element to be registered.
The attribute relationType describes the type of the relation to be associated with the new LCML or LUML model element to be registered through reference to the code list CR_RoleType.
The attribute sourceRole describes the type of the relation to be associated with the new LCML or LUML model element to be registered through reference to the code list CR_RoleDescription.
The attribute targetRole describes the type of the relation to be associated with the new LCML or LUML model element to be registered through reference to the code list CR_RoleDescription.

The code list CR_AttType describes the types of attributes that may be registered to extend the LCML or LUML meta language.
boolean - an attribute that can only have one of two possible values: true or false
integer - a whole number (not a fractional number) that can be positive, negative, or zero.
real - a number that can be used to measure a continuous one-dimensional quantity.
characterString - a string of characters. The string of characters represents a text string and may be in any alphabet or language.
codeList - a list of predetermined attribute values.

The class CR_RegisterClass is an abstract class that serves as a root for the different types of register item classes that are defined in subsequent clauses to support the different elements that may be registered to support classification systems. It inherits its attributes from RegisterComponents::RegisterItem from ISO 19135.
This subtype relationship establishes inheritance from the ISO 19135 RegisterComponents:RegisterItem to the CR_RegisterItem.

The class CR_DescriptiveElementRegister specifies a register for the extension of the meta languages defined in ISO 19144-2 and ISO 19144-3. This class specifies information about the register itself. It is a subclass of the class RE_Register which is itself a subclass of the class Register. Both Register and RE_Register are defined in ISO 19135.

In the case the Land Cover Land Use descriptive element register, the attribute name shall contain the character string: “LCLU Descriptive Element Register” followed with any other additional text used to make the register name unique. This provides a level of consistency to the naming and content summary description of this register to make it easier for a user to recognize the purpose of the register and to assist in coordination of a federated register if one is established.

UML:Expression.body: Register of LCLU meta-language elements used to extend LCML or LUML meta-languages"

UML:TaggedValue.value: In the case the Land Cover Land Use descriptive element register, the attribute "contentSummary" shall contain the character string: “Register of LCLU meta-language elements used to extend the LCML or LUML meta-language” followed with any other additional text used to additionally describe the register.

This class describes the registered item used to register a classification schema or legend. This class inherits the attributes from CR_RegisterItem. The attributes name, definition, legendReferenced and documentationReference are added to reference the external file containing the detailed representation of the specific classification schema or legend represented as an XML schema.

The attribute name overwrites the attribute name inherited from RE_RegisterItem and describes the name of the classification schema or legend used. This name is represented as a character string containing a compact and human-readable designator that is used to denote the name of the legend/schema. The value of the name is unique within a register. Multiple items of the same item class may use the same value for name but only one such item can have the status "valid" at a time.

The attribute definition overwrites the attribute definition inherited from RE_RegisterItem and provides a description of the of the classification schema or legend used. This attribute is made optional. A reference to the source documentation of the specification of the classification schema or legend used can be made through the RE_Reference mechanism defined in ISO 19135.

The attribute legendReference identifies the external file containing the detailed representation of the specific classification schema or legend represented as an XML schema. This XML schema is an instantiation of the meta language from ISO 19144-2 or ISO 19144-3 used to describe the classification schema or legend used. The reference is a URI.
The documentation can be referenced using the CI_CItation mechanism from ISO 19115-1.

This class describes the form of the registered item used to register a new Land Use activity in the LUML meta language. This class inherits the attributesfrom CR_ItemClass and adds the attributes: activityName, activityDefinition, associatedAttributes using the data type class CR_MetaLangAttribute and associatedRelations using the data type class CR_MetaLangRelation.
The attribute activityName describes the name of the new Land Use activity LUML model element to be registered.

The attribute activityDefinition describes the definition of the new Land Use activity LUML model element to be registered. A reference to the source of the definition may be made through the RE_Reference mechanism defined in ISO 19135.

The attribute associatedAttributes describes the attributes that may be associated with the new LUML model element to be registered. Each attribute is associated by name and must either already exist in ISO 19144-2 or ISO 19144-3 or other TC-211 standard such as, ISO 19103 or ISO 19115-2 or be registered using the CR_AttributeItem part of the register. There can be 0 or more attributes. Each attribute is described in CR_MetaLangAttributes.

The attribute associatedRelations describes the relations that may be associated with the new LUML model element to be registered. There is at least one relation. Each relation is described in the referenced class CR_MetaLangRelation.

This class provides the information needed to describe a role associated with a relation. It includes a name specified by the attribute roleName, a definition specified by the attribute roleDefinition, a multiplicity for the role specified by the attribute roleMultiplicity that references the code list CR_RoleMultiplicity and whether the relationship is navigable in the direction corresponding to the role as specified by the attribute roleNavigability where True means navigatable.
The attribute roleName describes the name of the role to be associated with the relation.

The attribute roleDefinition describes the definition of the role to be associated with the relation. A reference to the source of the definition may be made through the RE_Reference mechanism defined in ISO 19135.
The attribute roleMultiplicity describes the multiplicity of the relation to be associated with the relation through reference to the code list CR_RoleMultiplicity.

The attribute roleNavigability describes whether a relation is navigable in the direction corresponding to the role as a boolean value where True means navigatable. The default value is False (not navigable or undetermined) and is considered to be False if the attribute is not provided.
